<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Theme</strong> standardizes the <strong>concrete-value layer</strong> of a design system
    &mdash; the layer every benchmark system has and the web platform leaves to each library to reinvent.
    Web Everything already owns the <em>semantic</em> tier as <a href="/projects/webintents/">Web
    Intents</a>: <a href="/intents/density/">density</a>, <a href="/intents/surface/">surface</a> (a
    <code>0&ndash;5</code> elevation scale), typography, motion, and the theme-color dimensions
    (<code>scheme</code>/<code>contrast</code>/<code>accent</code>). What was missing is the layer those
    semantic roles <em>resolve into</em> &mdash; the primitive scales (spacing, radius, elevation/shadow,
    type ramp, color palette) and the per-component overrides. Web Theme is that layer, and nothing above
    it.
  </p>
  <p>
    It makes two decisions and inherits the rest from the platform. Tokens are authored and interchanged as
    <strong>DTCG 2025.10</strong> &mdash; the W3C Design Tokens format that reached its first stable version
    on 2025-10-28 &mdash; <em>adopted, not coined</em>, because a now-stable standard with 10+ tool
    implementations is the one place a Protocol is warranted (minimize lock-in: a protocol is the single
    escapable lock). And tokens compile to the <strong>native CSS runtime</strong> &mdash; custom
    properties + <code>@property</code>, <code>light-dark()</code>, relative-color, <code>color-mix()</code>
    &mdash; all Baseline since 2024, so there is no build-time theming engine to lock into.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not the intents, not a new vocabulary</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      The <strong>semantic tier is owned by <a href="/projects/webintents/">Web Intents</a></strong>, and
      Web Theme does <em>not</em> re-name it. The intents stay the UX-&ldquo;what&rdquo; (this surface is
      <em>elevated</em>, this region is <em>dense</em>); Web Theme supplies the concrete value that
      &ldquo;what&rdquo; points into (elevation 2 = <em>this</em> shadow token). Coining a parallel semantic
      naming was rejected (it would have intents and tokens disagree on role names). This is the structural
      answer to &ldquo;how do tokens relate to the theme-color intent&rdquo;: one tier beneath it, resolved
      <em>by</em> it. Ruling: <a href="/backlog/364-unified-design-token-theming-system/">#364</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

