<section id="protocol-design-tokens" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="how-it-works">Design Tokens Protocol (DTCG &harr; CSS)</h3>
  <p>
    The contract has two halves. <strong>Authoring/interchange</strong> is W3C DTCG 2025.10 &mdash; a
    vendor-neutral JSON the whole tooling ecosystem already reads (Style Dictionary, Tokens Studio, Figma,
    Terrazzo), so a token set is portable and a vendor swappable. <strong>Runtime</strong> is native CSS:
    every resolved token compiles to a custom property, and the theming axes resolve through Baseline CSS
    with no build-time engine. The default token set is complete; a consuming project overrides via DTCG
    <code>extends</code>, never authoring from scratch (config-extends-platform-default).
  </p>
  {% highlight "json" %}
// Authoring tier — DTCG 2025.10. Portable across Style Dictionary / Tokens Studio / Figma.
{
  "color": {
    "$type": "color",
    "blue": { "9":  { "$value": "oklch(0.55 0.18 256)" } },
    "accent": { "$value": "{color.blue.9}" }        // {group.token} aliasing
  },
  "space": {
    "$type": "dimension",
    "4": { "$value": "1rem" }
  },
  "radius": { "$type": "dimension", "md": { "$value": "0.5rem" } }
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  {% highlight "css" %}
/* Runtime tier — the compile output. One custom property per resolved token. */
:root {
  /* primitive tier */
  --color-blue-9: oklch(0.55 0.18 256);
  --space-4: 1rem;
  --radius-md: 0.5rem;
  /* component tier — a per-component override that ALIASES a primitive */
  --button-radius: var(--radius-md);
}

/* Typed numerics register via @property so they animate + validate. */
@property --button-radius {
  syntax: "<length>"; inherits: true; initial-value: 0.5rem;
}

/* Scheme resolves at runtime — no build step, no second token file. */
:root { color-scheme: light dark; }
.surface { background: light-dark(var(--color-bg-light), var(--color-bg-dark)); }

/* Accent derivation — one accent token derives a whole scale, contrast-gated. */
:root {
  --accent-9:  var(--color-accent);
  --accent-10: oklch(from var(--accent-9) calc(l - 0.06) c h);  /* relative color */
  --accent-a3: color-mix(in oklab, var(--accent-9) 12%, transparent);
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: 1rem;">
    <li><strong>DTCG adopted, not coined:</strong> the format is the one legitimate Protocol here. WE
      conforms to the W3C standard so tokens interop with the existing tool ecosystem &mdash; coining a
      WE-native schema would be lock-in for zero interop gain.</li>
    <li><strong>Native CSS is the only runtime:</strong> custom properties + <code>@property</code> +
      <code>light-dark()</code> + relative-color + <code>color-mix()</code>, all Baseline 2024. There is no
      theming engine to depend on; the output is plain CSS.</li>
    <li><strong>Contrast-validation gate (Fork 4, A&prime;):</strong> derived accent/state steps are
      validated against WCAG/APCA per step, so accessibility is by-default; hand-curated scales (Radix-style)
      are a brand-precision <em>override</em>, not the accessibility safety net.</li>
    <li><strong>Semantic tier excluded by design:</strong> the protocol fixes primitive + component +
      format + runtime. The semantic role names are the intents, which resolve <em>into</em> a primitive
      token &mdash; no parallel vocabulary is defined here.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="composition" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="composition">Composition With Other Standards</h3>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webintents/">Web Intents</a></strong> &mdash; owns the semantic tier
      (density, surface, typography, motion, theme-color). An intent's <code>accent</code>/elevation ref
      resolves into a Web Theme primitive token; the two never disagree on a role name.</li>
    <li><strong>theme-color intent (<a href="/backlog/010-gap-3-theme-color-intent/">#010</a>)</strong>
      &mdash; the still-unauthored intent whose <code>scheme</code>/<code>contrast</code>/<code>accent</code>
      dimensions are the theming axis; Web Theme supplies the concrete values they point into. Authoring that
      intent stays #010's separate <code>/new-standard</code> build, which this feeds.</li>
    <li><strong><a href="/projects/webvalidation/">Web Validation</a> / APCA-WCAG</strong> &mdash; the
      contrast-validation gate reuses an accessibility check, not a new one, to qualify derived steps.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="status" class="section-card">
  <h3 id="status">Status</h3>
  <p>
    Web Theme is in <strong>concept</strong> phase; the Design Tokens (DTCG &harr; CSS) protocol is specified
    here at <strong>draft</strong>. The project was ratified by
    <a href="/backlog/364-unified-design-token-theming-system/">#364</a> (the unified design-token / theming
    decision, grounded in a <a href="/research/design-token-theming-system/">prior-art survey</a> of the
    benchmark systems + the native CSS substrate). This page establishes Forks 1&ndash;2 &mdash; the project
    and the DTCG&harr;CSS mapping. The remaining graduated builds layer on top: the primitive + component
    token tiers and the platform default set (Fork 3), then the scheme/accent runtime + curated-override path
    (Fork 4).
  </p>
  <h4 style="margin-top: 1rem;">Open Questions</h4>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
    <li>Does the default token set ship as one DTCG document, or split per <code>$type</code> group
      (color/space/type) for selective <code>extends</code>?</li>
    <li>Component-tier overrides: authored as DTCG nodes that alias primitives, or emitted only at compile
      time from a component manifest?</li>
    <li>Is the WCAG/APCA contrast gate a build-time check, a runtime <code>@supports</code> fallback, or
      both?</li>
  </ul>
</section>
